WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.160
Welcome to the Data Science Hangout and hope everybody's having a great week.

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:16.160
I'm Rachel.

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:18.799
I lead our pro community at Posit.

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:23.680
And if you have not been here before, this is our open space to chat about data science

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:28.559
leadership, questions you're facing and forgetting to hear about what's going on in the world

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:30.840
of data across different industries.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:35.279
So we're here every Thursday at the same time, same place.

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:39.759
So if you are somewhere in the future watching this recording on YouTube, you can always

00:00:39.759 --> 00:00:45.799
add it to your calendar with the details and include it below.

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:51.240
Together we're all dedicated to making this a welcoming environment for everyone.

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:56.799
And we all love to hear from everybody, no matter your level of experience or area of

00:00:56.799 --> 00:00:57.799
work.

00:00:57.799 --> 00:00:59.000
We love to hear from you.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.120
It's also totally okay to just listen in here if you don't want to join in the conversation,

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:05.680
that's okay too.

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:11.059
But there's three ways you can jump in and ask questions or provide your own perspective.

00:01:11.059 --> 00:01:16.360
So you can always jump in by raising your hand here on Zoom and I'll be on the lookout.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:19.519
You can put questions in the Zoom chat.

00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:23.919
And if you do want me to read it out instead of you, maybe you're in a cafe or your dog's

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:28.760
barking or something, just put a little star next to your question in the Zoom chat.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:33.519
And then we also have a Slido link, which my colleagues will be sharing, oh, Tyler just

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:38.519
shared it right now, which they shared in the chat so you can ask questions anonymously

00:01:38.519 --> 00:01:39.519
too.

00:01:39.519 --> 00:01:44.000
With all that, thank you all so much for joining us here on this Thursday.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.080
I'm so excited to have Brad Weiner here with us as my co-host today.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:54.680
Brad is the Chief Data Officer at the University of Colorado, Boulder.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:58.680
And Brad, to get us going here, I'd love to have you just kind of jump in and introduce

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:04.019
yourself, share a little bit about your role and also something you like to do outside

00:02:04.019 --> 00:02:05.019
of work too.

00:02:05.019 --> 00:02:06.019
Yeah, great.

00:02:06.019 --> 00:02:09.279
So thanks so much, Rachel.

00:02:09.279 --> 00:02:14.479
I wanted to thank Rachel and everybody from the PASA team for being here.

00:02:14.479 --> 00:02:18.399
And I think on behalf of, and hello, Brian, good to see you.

00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:22.559
And then of course, it's easy to thank the community developers, but also just thanks

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:27.839
to everyone from the PASA team for helping us do cool stuff in our jobs and in our lives.

00:02:27.839 --> 00:02:31.679
So it's super fun to get to hang out with everyone.

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:32.880
My name is Brad Weiner.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:39.220
I am the Chief Data Officer here at the University of Colorado, Boulder.

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:43.279
And I got into this role in a fairly elliptical way.

00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:48.360
I, like many of you, are not technologists to start.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:51.779
I was actually a creative writing major in college.

00:02:51.779 --> 00:02:56.600
And I will die on this hill that data science and technical work is inherently creative

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:57.600
work.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:00.759
But over time, I started working for universities and in a lot of different roles.

00:03:00.759 --> 00:03:05.039
And at some point along the way, someone was like, hey, we need someone to do some reporting

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:06.039
and we need someone to do this.

00:03:06.039 --> 00:03:07.039
And I've always liked computers.

00:03:07.039 --> 00:03:08.320
I've always liked working with them.

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:14.039
So I'm like, yeah, sure, I'll give that a shot and thought it was unbelievably fun and

00:03:14.039 --> 00:03:17.199
interesting and a really cool puzzle to solve.

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:21.839
And over time, got more and more and more engaged in the data side of what colleges

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:24.479
and universities do.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:29.759
There's also a bump in the road where I was in graduate school and I took a statistics

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:30.759
course.

00:03:30.759 --> 00:03:34.240
By the way, hello to all my Minnesota pals out there, but I was at the University of

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:35.559
Minnesota.

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:39.559
And I had a professor who taught his statistics classes using R.

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:44.320
I mean, that was in about 2009 that I was first introduced to the whole concept of sort

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:49.880
of open source data science tools and just totally fell in love with it.

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:54.639
Just thought it was the most fun, most interesting thing that could possibly happen.

00:03:54.639 --> 00:04:02.279
And so that led to the opportunity to work on a data science team out in startup land.

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:06.839
And then finally to move here to CU Boulder to lead a data science team here and then

00:04:06.839 --> 00:04:10.800
eventually become the chief data officer.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.880
So that's like a little tiny bit of the journey.

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:18.160
I like to kind of give a quick overview of higher ed in general.

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:24.079
This is like maybe sort of boring for people, but I imagine many of you have gone to a university

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:28.480
somewhere around the world and you've had some post-secondary education.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:33.799
And universities are, they seem like they're like this one thing, right?

00:04:33.799 --> 00:04:38.799
But what a university is, is it's just like this collection of thousands of tiny little

00:04:38.799 --> 00:04:43.600
units and there's this sort of famous joke that's like, we're hundreds or thousands of

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:50.000
little micro units that are all unified by a common disagreement over parking or a common

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.079
disagreement over the temperatures in buildings or a common disagreement over our football

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:56.119
team or whatever.

00:04:56.119 --> 00:05:00.359
So let me just give you like a quick sense of what, you know, the president of the University

00:05:00.359 --> 00:05:04.880
of California in the 60s was a guy named Clark Kerr, and he referred to the modern university

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:06.519
as a multi-university.

00:05:06.519 --> 00:05:09.720
So let me just quickly kind of tell you why we're here.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:13.160
So the University of Colorado is a research university.

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:14.559
We have three missions.

00:05:14.559 --> 00:05:21.519
Our three missions are to engage in research and to create new knowledge out in the world,

00:05:21.519 --> 00:05:29.720
to teach and ask that knowledge on to students, and then finally to engage with the public

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:31.760
in what's called the public engagement mission.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:35.959
And that's translating your research efforts into things that can be broadly valuable.

00:05:35.959 --> 00:05:44.160
I mean, that really aligns very closely with what open source tools do.

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:46.260
But we also do a lot more.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:48.279
We produce art and creative works.

00:05:48.279 --> 00:05:50.440
We act as a venue for all kinds of things.

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:51.839
We're a community space.

00:05:51.839 --> 00:05:53.640
We have a football team.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:55.279
We have museums.

00:05:55.279 --> 00:05:56.519
We have a bowling alley.

00:05:56.519 --> 00:05:59.040
We provide healthcare and patient treatment.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:03.660
We at least at CU Boulder put a lot of stuff into outer space.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:07.959
We engage in economic development with the community here in Boulder and the state of

00:06:07.959 --> 00:06:11.399
Colorado and internationally.

00:06:11.399 --> 00:06:18.480
We at least at CU, we care and feed and sustain a live buffalo named Ralphie who runs around

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:19.959
on the football field.

00:06:19.959 --> 00:06:26.799
So the number of things that a single university are engaged in are quite limitless.

00:06:26.799 --> 00:06:31.079
And so why I like to lead with this whole spiel is that each one of those results in

00:06:31.079 --> 00:06:39.160
a very like almost limitless number of interesting kind of data science questions and problems.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:43.079
So that's sort of the intro.

00:06:43.079 --> 00:06:47.600
And so I definitely want to take most of the time to answer questions for you.

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:54.600
But just if you can imagine all of that complexity, every single one of those components can land

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:55.600
as a data question.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:07:01.559
And so why I am here and why our teams are here is to try and think through ways to make

00:07:01.559 --> 00:07:04.880
the student experience better, to make the faculty experience better, to make the staff

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:10.640
experience better, to make us work more effectively, work more efficiently, to make it so that

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:16.839
the people of Colorado have the best possible university that they can have.

00:07:16.839 --> 00:07:20.440
So with that, I'm loving this chat, by the way.

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.720
Yeah, I love that.

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:25.720
I love that intro too.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:26.720
But we forgot one thing.

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:28.920
What do you like to do outside of work as well?

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:30.519
What do I like to do outside of work?

00:07:30.519 --> 00:07:35.799
So recently I decided I needed to spend less time in front of the screen.

00:07:35.799 --> 00:07:41.880
And so I started taking piano lessons, which I encourage anyone, especially if you're sort

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:46.359
of later in life or midlife, to just try something totally new.

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:50.839
I walk into these piano lessons and the person before me is an eight-year-old girl who's

00:07:50.839 --> 00:07:52.399
amazing.

00:07:52.399 --> 00:07:57.440
And I'm like barely making it through the trouble staff.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:02.959
So I've really been enjoying learning to play piano and getting back into music.

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:03.959
I love that.

00:08:03.959 --> 00:08:04.959
Yeah.

00:08:04.959 --> 00:08:05.959
Thanks for that question, Rachel.

00:08:05.959 --> 00:08:06.959
Yeah.

00:08:06.959 --> 00:08:10.519
I just started taking guitar lessons a few weeks ago too.

00:08:10.519 --> 00:08:16.399
So like actually learning music theory again after like fourth grade flute class.

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:24.320
Patrick, I see you have your hand raised here to jump in with a question you want to jump in.

00:08:24.320 --> 00:08:25.320
Thanks, Rachel.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:26.320
Hi, everybody.

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:27.320
And thanks, Brad, for being here.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:28.320
I appreciate your time.

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:34.159
First, I just want to say I love universities too and like their weirdness and flaws and

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:36.719
all the kind of strange things about them.

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:41.080
But your enthusiasm for it and the way you articulated that just now was awesome.

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:42.080
So thank you very much.

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:46.679
I really enjoyed that and appreciate how into it you are.

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:50.080
My question is specific to the university system.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:55.080
If you have any examples of where you have really like influenced an institutional level

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:01.119
decision or maybe just for a school or department, but where you all have really shaped something

00:09:01.119 --> 00:09:05.159
like a real impact story from your data science work for the university.

00:09:05.159 --> 00:09:08.039
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:09:08.039 --> 00:09:13.039
And so Patrick, I'm guessing you have experience in academia or in higher ed.

00:09:13.039 --> 00:09:17.440
You seem to know the space pretty well.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.840
Making the data work is the easy part.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:26.080
Getting people to actually use the data and sort of inform policies is much trickier.

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:30.760
And I also always like to point to the fact that it really does take a village.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:38.119
We need all kinds of people to be invested and interested in a project.

00:09:38.119 --> 00:09:42.159
But there is one that we've sort of been pointing to lately, which was just released publicly

00:09:42.159 --> 00:09:45.640
to kind of quietly because it happened during finals.

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:50.919
One of the things that we've thought a lot about is ways to make it so that students

00:09:50.919 --> 00:09:53.919
have as easy of an experience as possible.

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:58.599
Because we really, really want students to be successful.

00:09:58.599 --> 00:10:03.640
Not just because that's like our core mission, but we're measured on that.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.159
All universities are measured on that in a lot of ways.

00:10:06.159 --> 00:10:08.559
And students want to go to a place where they're going to be successful.

00:10:08.559 --> 00:10:13.520
So we're constantly looking for what I would consider, and I know this is kind of gross

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.440
terminology for people in higher ed, but building a college degree really is a supply

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:22.159
chain problem.

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:26.919
You know, you need to have all of these constituent parts, and they need to land at the right

00:10:26.919 --> 00:10:30.919
time, and there's tons of dependencies, and those dependencies need to be built out years

00:10:30.919 --> 00:10:31.919
in advance.

00:10:31.919 --> 00:10:35.880
So if we don't have enough chemistry labs, that student doesn't get to take chemistry.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:40.239
And if not enough students take chemistry, they don't have the required courses, and

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:41.880
they can't graduate.

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:43.880
So we're constantly looking for these things.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:50.119
And one of the things that we have found is that students found that the prices of their

00:10:50.119 --> 00:10:56.320
textbooks to be something of a barrier.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.799
And one of the things that we actually found, we're not only trying to graduate students,

00:10:59.799 --> 00:11:04.239
but we're trying to graduate everybody as equitably as possible.

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:09.640
If the experience is one way for some students and one way for another group of students,

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:12.679
that is not considered success.

00:11:12.679 --> 00:11:15.880
And so what we were finding and what we had heard and what we learned is that students

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:20.840
were potentially choosing which courses to take based on the cost of the textbooks.

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:25.359
And there's also a little bit of this mode of understanding now that the students of

00:11:25.359 --> 00:11:29.799
today are used to subscription services.

00:11:29.799 --> 00:11:34.039
Nobody ever thinks like, oh, how many songs did I listen to on Spotify?

00:11:34.039 --> 00:11:35.200
Am I getting my money's worth?

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:41.559
They're just used to Netflix or these models where you just pay one price and you get everything.

00:11:41.559 --> 00:11:44.559
And it doesn't matter how much you use it or how little you use it.

00:11:44.559 --> 00:11:47.400
So Patrick, to answer your question, this is kind of the long way around, but to answer

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:52.679
your question, we just recently deployed, and you can read about it publicly, but we're

00:11:52.679 --> 00:11:56.719
one of the first handful, maybe a dozen or 15 schools that have gone in on this kind

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:03.440
of bookstore equity access model, which is basically students pay one price.

00:12:03.559 --> 00:12:06.960
And that gives them sort of financial stability, the predictability in their budgets, their

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:14.479
ability to budget on books, but also the ability to be really flexible in what they take.

00:12:14.479 --> 00:12:18.760
And by paying that one price, they get day one, what we call day one digital access.

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:22.000
And there's also evidence that students who, I mean, think about your college days, right?

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.239
You go and you take a class.

00:12:23.239 --> 00:12:26.280
The professor gives the old like, look to your left, look to your right, one of you

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:27.280
is going to fail.

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:29.200
And you're like, I'm out of here.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:31.760
And so then what you have to do is you have to go, you have to go back to the bookstore,

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:33.080
you have to return that book.

00:12:33.719 --> 00:12:37.640
And so we have found, and there's evidence that having digital immediate access to your

00:12:37.640 --> 00:12:40.719
books is actually a student success lever.

00:12:40.719 --> 00:12:44.880
And so for a variety of reasons, we wanted to implement this program.

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:51.239
And one of the things that we were asked to do is, what price should the bundle be?

00:12:51.239 --> 00:12:54.559
And if any of you have worked in pricing, it's a really complicated problem.

00:12:54.559 --> 00:12:59.559
If the price is too high, nobody participates and the whole thing kind of collapses on itself.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:03.559
And if it's too low, you don't cover your costs.

00:13:03.559 --> 00:13:08.799
And so we had a whole team of people who are sort of thinking through that problem.

00:13:08.799 --> 00:13:12.159
And Rachel was very clear.

00:13:12.159 --> 00:13:15.520
She's like, you do not need to shill for Posit.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:20.520
But we are happy to say that we used our super sweet Posit workbench setup to simulate a

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:23.479
whole bunch of different options.

00:13:23.479 --> 00:13:25.359
The data science team did that.

00:13:25.359 --> 00:13:33.080
And we were able to help them provide, to guide them on what that price was.

00:13:33.080 --> 00:13:34.080
And it got deployed out.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:37.359
And so next year, from what I understand, all undergraduates at CU Boulder will pay

00:13:37.359 --> 00:13:43.679
$279 a semester and get all of their books on day one.

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:47.039
And if they drop a class, then those books go away and the new ones come in and they

00:13:47.039 --> 00:13:49.359
just have access to their books.

00:13:49.359 --> 00:13:53.280
Patrick, I think it'll be valuable to follow up with me a year from now and see how well

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:54.320
we did.

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:57.320
Because this is a known unknown.

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:00.320
We're going to have to see where I landed.

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:01.960
That is a great example.

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:02.960
Thank you very much.

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:07.479
And really, not what I was expecting in terms of the example you choose, but just kind of

00:14:07.479 --> 00:14:12.599
demonstrates how broad the impact could be in an area that's so complex and diverse,

00:14:12.599 --> 00:14:13.599
like you described.

00:14:13.599 --> 00:14:14.599
So thank you.

00:14:14.599 --> 00:14:15.599
That's wonderful.

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:16.599
Yep.

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:17.599
You got it.

00:14:17.599 --> 00:14:18.599
Sorry, I need to read the chat.

00:14:18.599 --> 00:14:20.440
It's less than I was paying 20 years ago.

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:21.440
So that's...

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:22.440
Yeah.

00:14:22.599 --> 00:14:25.599
We'll see how we do.

00:14:25.599 --> 00:14:26.599
Yeah.

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:27.599
That's amazing.

00:14:27.599 --> 00:14:32.599
There's a lot of love for that example in the chat here too.

00:14:32.599 --> 00:14:37.119
I see, Abigail, you had asked a question in the chat a little bit earlier.

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:38.599
Do you want to jump in here?

00:14:38.599 --> 00:14:39.599
Thanks, Rachel.

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:40.599
Yeah.

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:43.919
This is something like multiple organizations I've been part of, I've been trying to figure

00:14:43.919 --> 00:14:46.159
out like what to use for data viz.

00:14:46.159 --> 00:14:49.960
So I see you guys are doing like a lot of Tableau dashboards and Tableau public.

00:14:49.960 --> 00:14:50.960
What was...

00:14:50.960 --> 00:14:56.280
So how did you think that through as an organization, like what data viz tools to use?

00:14:56.280 --> 00:14:58.280
So that is a great question.

00:14:58.280 --> 00:15:00.760
I'm sorry, your name is Abigail?

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:02.799
I didn't see where I can highlight.

00:15:02.799 --> 00:15:03.799
Yes.

00:15:03.799 --> 00:15:04.799
Awesome.

00:15:04.799 --> 00:15:06.679
So thanks for that great question.

00:15:06.679 --> 00:15:14.919
Data viz is eternally complicated because the technology is always moving.

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:21.400
And then I think it's also fair to point out that higher ed tends to be a fairly conservative

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:25.760
industry and it tends to buy things in like big ways.

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:33.919
So hey, we want to spin up a Posit server and just test it out on 10 users is usually

00:15:33.919 --> 00:15:38.599
a little bit different than like, what is the best way that we can like use our tremendous

00:15:38.599 --> 00:15:42.280
buying power to have everybody in the same tool?

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:49.119
And so it's always kind of striking a balance, but a lot of universities have gone in pretty

00:15:49.119 --> 00:15:56.679
deep on, I don't know if I'm allowed to say it, but on Tableau.

00:15:56.679 --> 00:16:01.559
If a third of you hang up right now, I will not blame you.

00:16:01.559 --> 00:16:02.559
You can say whatever you want.

00:16:02.559 --> 00:16:10.440
No, I know, but I'm just, so anyway, Tableau is kind of an industry standard across what's

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:12.000
called institutional research.

00:16:12.719 --> 00:16:16.119
So universities have all these compliance regulations, they need to report on a bunch

00:16:16.119 --> 00:16:17.119
of stuff.

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:24.119
And so Tableau is just like pretty commonly used and has been for about the last 10 years.

00:16:24.119 --> 00:16:31.919
So we do use no comment Bill, but you're potentially correct.

00:16:31.919 --> 00:16:38.080
But one of the things that we're constantly thinking through are ways to leverage more

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:39.239
modern technology.

00:16:39.239 --> 00:16:45.799
And then one of the things that's a really interesting problem space is that Tableau

00:16:45.799 --> 00:16:54.000
doesn't necessarily provide semantic HTML underneath as part of its API calls.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.280
And what that means is that it's actually a little bit difficult to access with screen

00:16:58.280 --> 00:16:59.359
readers.

00:16:59.359 --> 00:17:02.080
And of course, we're a public university, we put out a bunch of public data.

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:08.400
And one of the things we want to make sure we do is have as accessible of visualizations

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:12.400
and accessible access to our information as possible.

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:19.640
And so Tableau provides a ton of value for a lot of reasons, and people really like being

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:22.239
able to explore the data.

00:17:22.239 --> 00:17:30.040
But we are also looking at other ways to potentially visualize information and put out data.

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:33.719
There's also just people who want to use open source tools.

00:17:33.719 --> 00:17:41.599
And so there's always the conversation of like, how big can we scale things like Flask

00:17:41.599 --> 00:17:43.920
or Streamlit or Shiny?

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:48.760
And I know that those are amazing options, and I love them.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:54.319
But we haven't gotten to a point of like, sort of like institution wide buying.

00:17:54.319 --> 00:17:59.079
So we pick Abigail in the way that we pick a lot of things, which is through a process

00:17:59.079 --> 00:18:03.880
called satisficing, which is like, well, the university up the road is doing it seems

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:04.880
good enough.

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:05.880
It'll be fine.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:08.000
We'll go with that.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:16.319
And then we're mostly happy with what we get until something better comes along.

00:18:16.319 --> 00:18:20.920
And all of the open source questions I totally agree with.

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:22.959
And we just haven't gotten there yet.

00:18:22.959 --> 00:18:26.439
So those of you who work in like your cool startup with 50 people, and you're like, oh,

00:18:26.439 --> 00:18:28.880
well, we were in Streamlit for three weeks, and it didn't work for this.

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:32.439
And now we're going to pivot over to Shiny or whatever.

00:18:32.439 --> 00:18:39.119
It's just a lot harder for us to move the sort of gravity of such a big organization.

00:18:39.119 --> 00:18:44.280
And I will say Tableau has a lot of advantages, it has a lot of functionality, although it

00:18:44.280 --> 00:18:45.719
does not have a spell check.

00:18:45.719 --> 00:18:51.280
So what does that mean?

00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:55.800
I see Lisa had a follow up to your story that you shared about the book pricing.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:18:58.800
Lisa, do you want to jump in?

00:18:59.719 --> 00:19:05.119
I'm lunching right now, which is rather early for Minnesota, but so it is.

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:10.400
Yeah, I was just curious if you shared out and maybe it's a little too early, any of

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:18.280
the findings about the books, because I know having been in academia, that, you know, at

00:19:18.280 --> 00:19:22.319
least McAllister was sort of thinking about that problem as well.

00:19:22.319 --> 00:19:24.959
Yeah, we're still pretty new to it.

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:32.119
And higher ed, like seemingly has, like never has a mythical first mover.

00:19:32.119 --> 00:19:35.560
But there are a couple of schools that have gone in on this, including University of California

00:19:35.560 --> 00:19:37.560
at Davis.

00:19:37.560 --> 00:19:43.000
And so they're the ones who have sort of the most information about it.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:48.400
I would be happy to share and, you know, talk with the people who actually built this out.

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:51.400
But right now we are launching it for this fall.

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:54.160
And so it'll be a little while before we have any like real outcome data.

00:19:54.359 --> 00:20:00.040
But of course, the really exciting part will be, can we measure whether or not that particular

00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:03.839
intervention had an impact on student success?

00:20:03.839 --> 00:20:08.719
And so probably a year or two years from now, we'll have some like real data on what it

00:20:08.719 --> 00:20:09.719
all meant.

00:20:09.719 --> 00:20:14.280
Right now, we were just trying to get the thing out the door and put a price on it.

00:20:14.280 --> 00:20:19.319
But all the cool stuff is yet to happen.

00:20:19.319 --> 00:20:21.199
Also hi, Lisa.

00:20:21.239 --> 00:20:26.479
I know Lisa from, you know, tangentially through the Twin Cities data science community.

00:20:26.479 --> 00:20:30.400
So it's good to see, good to see my Minnesota peeps in here.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:31.400
Likewise.

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:32.400
I see.

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:33.400
Oh, sorry.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:40.800
I see, Alan, you had asked a question a little bit earlier in the chat.

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:42.280
Do you want to jump in here next?

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:43.280
Yeah, sure.

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:44.280
Hi, Brad.

00:20:44.280 --> 00:20:45.280
And everybody.

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:47.280
It's super fun today.

00:20:47.359 --> 00:20:53.119
Brad, I'm really curious where your role lives within the institution.

00:20:53.119 --> 00:20:55.520
Like is it, are you strongly connected to IT?

00:20:55.520 --> 00:20:57.560
Are you in administration?

00:20:57.560 --> 00:21:01.479
And I've got to think that where you kind of live organizationally has got impact on

00:21:01.479 --> 00:21:05.920
like how work comes to you, how you get to decide what to do, how you're prioritized,

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:06.920
all those kinds of things.

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:09.800
Just if you could kind of expand on that, that'd be great.

00:21:09.800 --> 00:21:12.119
Yeah, that's a great question, Alan.

00:21:12.119 --> 00:21:18.119
I work in the sort of administrative side.

00:21:18.119 --> 00:21:22.880
But I have a really good, I have a colleague who's a chief data officer, and he will basically

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:29.599
say that if you run or work with a data organization, and I would probably apply this to any of

00:21:29.599 --> 00:21:36.000
your organizations, although I only, I know my industry best, but if you are a centralized

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:42.319
data team, and you're not serving everybody, you're failing.

00:21:42.319 --> 00:21:46.400
And maybe that's a little bit harsh, because it might not be set up that way everywhere.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:52.719
But for us, we want to support academic units, we want to support academic leadership, we

00:21:52.719 --> 00:21:57.920
want to support colleges and schools and programs, just as much as we want to support the auxiliary

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:02.959
units parking in the bookstore and finance and budget and enrollment and all of those

00:22:02.959 --> 00:22:03.959
things.

00:22:03.959 --> 00:22:13.079
So our role in the most big picture way is to support students, faculty and staff, and

00:22:13.079 --> 00:22:17.359
to engage in those three missions as much as we possibly can.

00:22:17.359 --> 00:22:21.920
And parsing out where the boundaries are is really, really tough.

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:25.959
So people on my team, for instance, we have a whole team that does surveys.

00:22:25.959 --> 00:22:33.280
And those surveys help understand how students are engaging on campus, what their sense of

00:22:33.599 --> 00:22:36.119
belonging is, what type of activities they're participating in.

00:22:36.119 --> 00:22:40.719
But one of the things we do is we run what are called the faculty course questionnaires

00:22:40.719 --> 00:22:41.719
for all of campus.

00:22:41.719 --> 00:22:45.839
So every time you get to the end of semester, and you go, you know, this professor was great,

00:22:45.839 --> 00:22:51.199
or this professor wasn't so great, all of those data are sort of publicly available

00:22:51.199 --> 00:22:55.119
and come through this data group.

00:22:55.119 --> 00:22:59.719
And that provides us opportunities to really talk about student success through the lens

00:22:59.719 --> 00:23:06.760
of teaching and learning and through the lens of how students are engaging in the classroom.

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:11.119
And then, of course, there's a whole discipline of kind of what's known as learning analytics.

00:23:11.119 --> 00:23:14.040
So if you Google that, there's all kinds of papers that are out there.

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:21.359
But you know, the degree to which students in different classes perform on different

00:23:21.359 --> 00:23:28.839
types of exercises or different types of, you know, in different types of learning environments,

00:23:28.959 --> 00:23:30.319
also matters.

00:23:30.319 --> 00:23:36.520
So I, a bunch of years ago, I had the opportunity to work with a kind of multi-institutional

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:39.760
team from around the Big Ten.

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:46.560
And we were trying to understand whether or not there was any difference in academic performance

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:53.800
based on a student's self-reported gender identity in introductory STEM classes.

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:57.359
And it was really fascinating, because one, it was like an amazing data engineering problem.

00:23:57.359 --> 00:24:00.560
And you're like, well, we have a five-hour chemistry class, and they have a three-hour

00:24:00.560 --> 00:24:01.560
chemistry class.

00:24:01.560 --> 00:24:02.800
Are those the same?

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:08.319
So like, harmonizing data across a bunch of universities was like, insanely complicated.

00:24:08.319 --> 00:24:14.560
But it delved really deeply into, you know, the unit of analysis of like the individual

00:24:14.560 --> 00:24:15.920
course.

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:18.359
And then, of course, you can go even lower, like, what about the section?

00:24:18.359 --> 00:24:19.560
What about the instructor?

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:23.920
And we are here to support efforts like that as well.

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:30.199
Which by the way, is why this job is so epically fun, because for three weeks, you're talking

00:24:30.199 --> 00:24:34.880
about bookstore prices, and then you're trying to figure out like, why courses that have

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:38.560
just a midterm and a final are different from courses that have a variety of assessments

00:24:38.560 --> 00:24:39.839
along the way.

00:24:39.839 --> 00:24:43.199
So I don't know, that was kind of a long answer.

00:24:43.199 --> 00:24:48.719
But the gist is like, we live where we live organizationally, but we have touch points

00:24:48.719 --> 00:24:50.839
across the university.

00:24:50.839 --> 00:24:57.760
And if we didn't, we wouldn't have as good of an ability to answer the really hard questions

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:01.599
where those two things land in exactly the same spot.

00:25:01.599 --> 00:25:07.040
You know, a student might not be successful because they might have basic needs problems,

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:12.160
they might need additional financial aid, they might not have a sense of belonging,

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:14.439
they might not be engaged in the community.

00:25:14.439 --> 00:25:18.719
They might also just really not be that good at math and need help with that.

00:25:18.719 --> 00:25:24.880
And all of that is part of the kind of interconnected sort of supply chain.

00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:25.880
That's great.

00:25:25.880 --> 00:25:26.880
Thank you.

00:25:26.880 --> 00:25:33.760
It sounds like such a really fascinating place to work with so much variety of problems and

00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:38.400
teams and people, like juggling a ton, but it sounds really, really neat.

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:39.400
Thanks.

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:42.680
Yeah, of course, it's completely wild.

00:25:42.680 --> 00:25:43.880
But it is fun.

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:45.719
It's an incredible amount of fun.

00:25:45.719 --> 00:25:46.719
Definitely.

00:25:46.719 --> 00:25:51.239
Yeah, it's really interesting to hear about the different variety of problems you get

00:25:51.239 --> 00:25:53.400
to work on.

00:25:53.400 --> 00:26:00.079
I think when we were talking a bit earlier, Brad, you mentioned that there aren't that

00:26:00.079 --> 00:26:03.959
many schools today that have a chief data officer.

00:26:03.959 --> 00:26:12.000
And I was wondering for schools who are maybe like in that spot of starting out to or like

00:26:12.319 --> 00:26:17.160
starting this role of chief data officer, if you have any tips to share them?

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:25.359
Yeah, I get this question pretty often.

00:26:25.359 --> 00:26:31.760
And so I'm gonna get my numbers a little bit wrong, but there's roughly 4000 or 5000 institutions

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:35.680
in the United States that receive title for funding.

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:39.119
Maybe it's actually probably a little bit higher, but that's everything from like, the

00:26:39.119 --> 00:26:43.880
California Barber College to Stanford.

00:26:43.880 --> 00:26:47.599
And that's basically title for funding means, you know, that they're eligible for federal

00:26:47.599 --> 00:26:51.880
student loans, or, well, that's, that's probably it.

00:26:51.880 --> 00:26:55.719
They're probably in the, you know, in the Higher Education Act, which Congress never

00:26:55.719 --> 00:26:56.719
reauthorizes.

00:26:56.719 --> 00:26:59.359
So we're always under like 20 year old rules.

00:26:59.359 --> 00:27:04.560
But there's 1000s and 1000s and 1000s of universities, and I'll just get on my soapbox for four seconds

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:10.239
to say, remember that number, the next time you read in the New York Times or the Wall

00:27:10.239 --> 00:27:14.680
Street Journal or the Washington Post that it's so hard to get into college.

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:15.719
It's not.

00:27:15.719 --> 00:27:20.400
We have so many choices, and most schools admit most students.

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:25.160
So I always like to just tell people like, the national media does not paint a very good

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:30.119
picture of the higher ed landscape at all.

00:27:30.119 --> 00:27:36.599
Off the soapbox of those two, from what I understand, there's probably 50 or so chief

00:27:36.599 --> 00:27:41.640
data officers or fewer people with that title.

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:46.959
There is a very traditional function in higher ed called institutional research, which sort

00:27:46.959 --> 00:27:50.739
of reports out all the numbers to the federal government, and they typically do this kind

00:27:50.739 --> 00:27:52.640
of work.

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:58.599
So I'm not trying to pick on you, Lisa, but they're at Macalester in St. Paul, they actually

00:27:58.599 --> 00:28:03.280
have a really amazing institutional research office that's run by really cool people.

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:06.920
But if you've worked in higher ed, you've at some point bumped into your kind of IR

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:07.920
group.

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:12.000
If you want to know anything about a university, these data are publicly available.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:16.319
And so there's someone who submits all of those data, and it's usually IR.

00:28:16.319 --> 00:28:22.040
But what's happening more and more is institutions are realizing that their data is this core

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:28.400
institutional asset, and that the more value that can be gotten out of those data, the

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:32.000
better the institution can do, and the better that they can support students.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:36.359
There's also a growing sort of sense that with the regulatory framework and with compliance

00:28:36.359 --> 00:28:40.239
frameworks and what the need for data governance and what the need for sort of more standardized

00:28:40.239 --> 00:28:45.400
policies around data, that, oh, look, we have an iPads key holder, look at that, cool, nice

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:48.119
to see you, George.

00:28:48.119 --> 00:28:55.760
But the conversation around how do we broadly manage our data is something that a chief

00:28:55.760 --> 00:28:58.479
data officer should be responsible for.

00:28:58.479 --> 00:29:03.160
And I wouldn't say it's like a weekly thing, but I'd say that probably like once a month,

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:08.280
some university reaches out to me on LinkedIn and is like, should we have a chief data officer?

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:09.280
What does that mean?

00:29:09.280 --> 00:29:12.160
What does the sort of construct look like in higher ed?

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:18.079
And just like it was a growing trend in industry probably over the last 10 years, it's

00:29:18.079 --> 00:29:22.599
now sort of catching up in higher ed.

00:29:22.599 --> 00:29:27.119
And yes, there's a little bit of a chat, iPads is the integrated post-secondary education

00:29:27.119 --> 00:29:28.680
data system.

00:29:28.680 --> 00:29:34.880
If you want to know like the number of enrolled Asian students at the University of Texas

00:29:34.880 --> 00:29:38.719
El Paso, it's all in there, and it's publicly available.

00:29:38.719 --> 00:29:39.719
Thank you.

00:29:39.719 --> 00:29:40.719
Yep.

00:29:40.719 --> 00:29:43.760
I always do a double check on acronyms.

00:29:43.760 --> 00:29:44.760
Yep.

00:29:44.959 --> 00:29:47.560
Deepa, I see you had a question in the chat.

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.359
Do you want to jump in here next?

00:29:49.359 --> 00:29:50.359
Sure.

00:29:50.359 --> 00:29:51.359
Thanks, Rachel.

00:29:51.359 --> 00:29:54.880
If I get a cough attack, I might hand it back to you to complete the question.

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:56.760
I'll be ready.

00:29:56.760 --> 00:30:01.000
This has been really fascinating to learn about the setting of university and kind of

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.040
problems that you have.

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:07.680
I'm a data scientist at Microsoft, and usually in a business setting, I know the challenge

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:14.280
that you spoke of is someone actually taking the action on the analysis you're doing is

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:16.199
a really big challenge.

00:30:16.199 --> 00:30:21.920
And so on here, a lot of times we don't pick up analysis that could be interesting because

00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:26.280
we don't have the identified stakeholders that would actually take the action or willing

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:28.640
to take the action, but it's also chicken and egg.

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:32.280
Like if they don't see the analysis, they don't know what possible action they could

00:30:32.280 --> 00:30:33.920
take.

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:36.439
So how do you overcome that challenge?

00:30:36.439 --> 00:30:37.839
How do you pick out the projects?

00:30:37.839 --> 00:30:42.800
How do you prioritize them considering you mentioned such a vast variety of projects

00:30:42.839 --> 00:30:43.839
you're able to take?

00:30:45.839 --> 00:30:57.160
Yeah, I would say carefully and imperfectly, you know, and I think it's one of the coolest

00:30:57.160 --> 00:30:59.599
things and I have to give a hat to deposit into Rachel.

00:30:59.599 --> 00:31:03.560
One of the coolest things about getting in a room like this is realizing that we all

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:05.359
have the same challenges.

00:31:05.359 --> 00:31:10.079
You know, I always had this idea like, oh, you work at Amazon, you work at Microsoft,

00:31:10.079 --> 00:31:11.400
like they've solved everything.

00:31:12.199 --> 00:31:13.599
And I've worked in higher ed, right?

00:31:13.599 --> 00:31:17.439
Like this place, it's been here since 1876.

00:31:17.439 --> 00:31:22.640
It's not going anywhere soon, but it's certainly decentralized and compartmentalized and has

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:25.199
those same type of organizational challenges.

00:31:25.199 --> 00:31:29.959
And I'm not bagging on CU, I'm bagging on, you know, I'm not even bagging on, I'm describing

00:31:29.959 --> 00:31:32.760
the reality of being in a university environment.

00:31:33.119 --> 00:31:47.319
And I would say that mostly we take on projects in a what will ostensibly have the largest

00:31:47.319 --> 00:31:52.640
potential impact for students or for what we're trying to do.

00:31:52.640 --> 00:31:58.359
There's also a little bit of a conversation that I think I've thought deeply about DeepShot,

00:31:58.359 --> 00:32:01.479
which is like, what is within your span of control?

00:32:01.719 --> 00:32:08.880
And sometimes it's like, it's not, it's, you know, and this might come across as the easy

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:15.520
road out, but it's like, what are things that we could directly impact or influence?

00:32:17.079 --> 00:32:23.199
And then there are also times where it is the decision is made in ways that I refer to as

00:32:23.199 --> 00:32:27.920
like, you're bringing water to the desert, where occasionally there are people that have

00:32:27.920 --> 00:32:32.400
nothing, they are just totally out in the open.

00:32:32.400 --> 00:32:38.000
And so on that like dimension of like, what's easy for us versus what's valuable to them is

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:43.760
like such in the sweet spot, because the simplest, most basic thing, it's like someone's just

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:48.880
been asking forever, like, all I need is this one thing and to be able to get at it routinely.

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:56.760
And you're like, hold my beer, let's focus the sprint, let's focus the cycles on that one

00:32:56.760 --> 00:33:03.400
thing. And those tend to be the situations where people come back and they're like, thank you so,

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:06.839
so much, we just needed this one dashboard.

00:33:06.839 --> 00:33:13.160
So I would say like, you know, if there's the thing that's easy for you and high value to

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:15.479
someone else, that's worthwhile.

00:33:15.479 --> 00:33:22.760
If there's something where you really feel like it's totally within your galaxy to be like,

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:27.079
hey, we had this finding, that finding suggests we shouldn't do this again.

00:33:27.719 --> 00:33:30.280
You're the person who's directly responsible for that.

00:33:31.319 --> 00:33:32.760
Don't do that again.

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:38.599
And like, that's right within your sort of frame of reference or within your span of control.

00:33:39.959 --> 00:33:45.800
And then, of course, as someone who just in case you can't tell, I'm kind of a wacky guy.

00:33:46.359 --> 00:33:53.640
I really value fun and joy and being a little bit weird, which I think is okay.

00:33:54.280 --> 00:34:01.319
And that one tiny corner of your whole portfolio should just be that random thing that seems like

00:34:01.319 --> 00:34:04.839
it's going to be a ton of fun to work on because those are the kinds of things that keep people

00:34:05.479 --> 00:34:06.119
engaged.

00:34:06.680 --> 00:34:11.800
And a lot of times it isn't like fun in some whimsical way, but it's just new, like this

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:12.600
bookstore thing.

00:34:13.159 --> 00:34:14.600
That was hard work.

00:34:14.600 --> 00:34:18.280
It was a complicated problem, but it was probably like five weeks of work.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.320
It was time boxed and it was that one thing.

00:34:21.320 --> 00:34:24.520
And then we passed it on and we're like, oh, that was cool.

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:28.280
We got to run tens of thousands of simulations on student opt-out behavior.

00:34:28.919 --> 00:34:33.639
Now back to our regularly scheduled program and we kind of can focus on the core stuff again.

00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:35.719
So is that helpful?

00:34:36.360 --> 00:34:37.320
No, it definitely is.

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:43.800
And it's great to see like how that value to effort constant measurement, like it has

00:34:43.800 --> 00:34:45.560
to be done in almost any setting.

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:48.120
It's common and it's constant.

00:34:48.120 --> 00:34:50.040
So thank you so much for sharing.

00:34:50.040 --> 00:34:53.879
And you did ask another question about like, how do you convince people to use the data?

00:34:54.600 --> 00:35:03.239
And that is, I think, you know, it just takes time and it takes trust and it takes effort.

00:35:03.239 --> 00:35:10.040
And it's also a recognition that it is not a linear path of like, we're getting better

00:35:10.040 --> 00:35:10.840
and better and better.

00:35:10.840 --> 00:35:12.439
And every single time there's more trust.

00:35:12.439 --> 00:35:15.320
It's like you go from step one to step two, and that's great.

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:17.000
And step two to step three, and that's great.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:18.360
And then people start coming to you more.

00:35:18.360 --> 00:35:24.360
And then you totally box something and you're back to step one because the thing went sideways.

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:31.320
And so I like to think that organizations are more resilient than we think they are.

00:35:31.959 --> 00:35:36.600
And that mistakes are sort of less damaging than we think they are in most cases.

00:35:37.399 --> 00:35:41.080
And so people shouldn't be too hard on themselves.

00:35:41.080 --> 00:35:44.439
If you're like, we found this thing and then people go, oh, that's cool.

00:35:44.439 --> 00:35:45.399
Right on.

00:35:45.399 --> 00:35:47.320
We're still going to do this other thing.

00:35:47.320 --> 00:35:51.159
And you're like, but you might not want to do that because the data say this.

00:35:53.159 --> 00:35:59.879
And I will say that like higher ed is especially prone to folklore and to, you know, and to

00:36:01.320 --> 00:36:04.600
people believing that their experience is sort of outweighing data.

00:36:04.600 --> 00:36:05.639
That's changing a lot.

00:36:06.360 --> 00:36:08.280
But one of the most fun parts about working in higher ed,

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:11.080
and this is one of the things that I was talking to Rachel about, is that

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:16.040
if you work in some industries, finding the inefficiencies is really hard

00:36:16.679 --> 00:36:20.199
because all of the inefficiencies have already been found.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:23.959
And in higher ed, they're kind of like all over the place.

00:36:23.959 --> 00:36:25.560
So it's pretty cool.

00:36:26.679 --> 00:36:28.919
But to give you guys a quick story about folklore,

00:36:28.919 --> 00:36:33.320
has anyone ever heard the myth that students choose which college they're going to go to

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:35.879
based on the weather on the day that they visit campus?

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:37.719
Anyone ever been down that one?

00:36:39.159 --> 00:36:39.560
I have.

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:41.159
Someone has?

00:36:41.159 --> 00:36:41.399
Yeah.

00:36:41.399 --> 00:36:41.959
Oh, man.

00:36:41.959 --> 00:36:43.560
I was, I really wanted to go to school,

00:36:43.560 --> 00:36:45.320
but it was rainy and terrible.

00:36:45.320 --> 00:36:46.439
There's no way I'm going there.

00:36:48.679 --> 00:36:55.879
So it's maybe a little bit of an admissions joke, but there is some mythology around that.

00:36:56.679 --> 00:36:58.760
I happen to used to work at the University of Minnesota.

00:36:58.760 --> 00:37:01.080
Minnesota has famously great weather.

00:37:01.639 --> 00:37:06.040
And I tested that assumption and it turns out to be false.

00:37:07.320 --> 00:37:10.840
And that included pulling hour by hour data,

00:37:11.959 --> 00:37:15.879
weather data for every single day for like going back to years and years and years

00:37:15.879 --> 00:37:18.199
and matching that up with when students visited.

00:37:18.199 --> 00:37:21.479
But to make it even more interesting, I know I'm talking to a bunch of data people,

00:37:21.479 --> 00:37:23.560
so you're all gonna be like, how did you do that?

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:25.879
I actually calculated not the weather on campus,

00:37:25.879 --> 00:37:29.959
but I calculated the delta of the weather on campus from where they came.

00:37:29.959 --> 00:37:32.439
Because I'm imagining someone from Southern California being like,

00:37:32.439 --> 00:37:34.280
wow, this is a shocking difference.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.080
And I modeled that like in every possible way.

00:37:39.080 --> 00:37:45.399
It was full on p-hacking data torture and I couldn't find anything to support that assumption.

00:37:46.439 --> 00:37:49.800
So the next time you hear that one, college admissions people,

00:37:50.919 --> 00:37:56.040
I tested it in truly one of the worst climates or the most extreme climates in America.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:37:57.320
And it's not true.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:01.080
That is such an interesting, this is absolutely love it.

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:03.560
Thank you for your great question.

00:38:03.560 --> 00:38:04.060
Thank you.

00:38:05.320 --> 00:38:09.800
I see Michael had asked a question in the chat and there's stars, so I'm going to read it.

00:38:09.800 --> 00:38:15.639
But it was, Brad, do you have any experiences or stories in using data science techniques

00:38:15.639 --> 00:38:20.919
to attempt to measure the effectiveness of CU's strategic communication efforts?

00:38:20.919 --> 00:38:26.040
Particularly in terms of things like, well, I guess this past example could kind of tie to this,

00:38:26.919 --> 00:38:30.120
but particularly in terms of things like recruiting effectiveness

00:38:30.120 --> 00:38:33.000
or public sentiment to university outreach efforts.

00:38:33.879 --> 00:38:37.000
Yeah, that's a copy of the question over into the chat again too.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:38.360
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:38:38.360 --> 00:38:42.360
We have a lot of connections with what at universities are called,

00:38:42.360 --> 00:38:44.040
is called like enrollment management.

00:38:44.840 --> 00:38:47.000
And they ask questions like that all the time.

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:53.080
And I don't want to go too much into the details because

00:38:54.040 --> 00:38:57.639
it's sort of complicated to tease out.

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:03.479
But that is sort of a really common set of questions that are asked,

00:39:03.479 --> 00:39:06.760
which is like, really, what is the effectiveness of anything?

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:10.280
What is the effectiveness of a virtual visit versus an on-campus visit?

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:15.080
What is the effectiveness of an email versus a paper mailing?

00:39:16.120 --> 00:39:22.760
And those are the types of things that are routinely asked.

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:29.000
And that if you work in an organization that does sort of marketing work

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.560
or does communications work, those are also, I think,

00:39:31.560 --> 00:39:36.679
some of the highest value conversations to have in data science land.

00:39:36.679 --> 00:39:41.639
Because so often what we do is very tough to append a specific cost

00:39:41.639 --> 00:39:44.199
or a specific sort of ROI to.

00:39:45.719 --> 00:39:48.520
And so there are things like that where you're like, look,

00:39:48.600 --> 00:39:51.560
you know, we sent out this mailer.

00:39:51.560 --> 00:39:52.760
Did it work or did it not?

00:39:52.760 --> 00:39:56.439
We sent out this email communication.

00:39:56.439 --> 00:39:57.399
Did it work or did it not?

00:39:57.399 --> 00:39:58.439
Or what was the effect of that?

00:39:58.439 --> 00:40:00.280
Or what was the effect of that on different students?

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:03.639
And, you know, email is basically free.

00:40:03.639 --> 00:40:09.800
So it's sort of a arcane and not very important research question.

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:13.639
But there are questions of like, you know,

00:40:13.639 --> 00:40:17.320
this whole combination of communications, what do those do?

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:22.679
And if they are found to have limited impact,

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:28.520
then it's easy or tends to be easy to make that argument of like,

00:40:28.520 --> 00:40:31.080
you really should pivot these dollars to something else.

00:40:32.760 --> 00:40:36.919
And enrollment management is becoming increasingly scientific.

00:40:36.919 --> 00:40:37.879
I mean, it really is.

00:40:38.520 --> 00:40:40.040
There's a guy, his name is Brock Tybert.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:41.959
He's going to be mad at me that I mentioned his name.

00:40:41.959 --> 00:40:45.080
But he thinks of it as like a science, enrollment science, you know,

00:40:45.080 --> 00:40:49.000
because what you have are millions of high school graduates.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:54.760
And you need to land a class that is big enough to, you know,

00:40:54.760 --> 00:40:57.000
it needs to be big enough to support your operations.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:58.520
It needs to be the right size.

00:40:58.520 --> 00:41:00.840
But you also need to have that across different majors

00:41:00.840 --> 00:41:03.000
and different colleges and different programs.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:04.840
And you need balance across all these different things.

00:41:04.840 --> 00:41:09.000
So if you Google the concept of enrollment management

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:12.280
or enrollment science, you'll find a bazillion papers out there

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.199
on how this happens.

00:41:14.919 --> 00:41:18.600
And it starts with like millions and millions and millions

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:19.719
and millions and millions of people

00:41:22.600 --> 00:41:25.479
whose name gets entered into a database, basically.

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:29.719
And this is also a really fascinating conversation now

00:41:29.719 --> 00:41:33.800
because COVID had a dramatic effect on this entire industry.

00:41:34.439 --> 00:41:39.159
One of the big things was that many, many, many more schools

00:41:39.159 --> 00:41:42.679
are now no longer requiring the SAT or the ACT.

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:47.080
And in so doing, the SAT and ACT were the primary source

00:41:47.080 --> 00:41:48.439
of a lot of these names.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:52.600
And so even like getting the kind of marketing apparatus

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:56.520
going around student enrollment is a different story

00:41:56.520 --> 00:41:58.360
than it was even three to five years ago.

00:42:00.360 --> 00:42:02.679
But the short answer is yes.

00:42:02.679 --> 00:42:05.159
And you can find all kinds of resources

00:42:05.159 --> 00:42:07.080
and information online about that.

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:09.479
You can also look me up on LinkedIn.

00:42:09.479 --> 00:42:12.280
And I used to work at a startup that did that very thing,

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:15.399
which was email marketing campaigns

00:42:15.399 --> 00:42:17.320
to prospective college students.

00:42:17.320 --> 00:42:19.639
And we had a ton of research and information

00:42:19.639 --> 00:42:20.840
on how to do that well.

00:42:24.199 --> 00:42:27.479
I'll share your LinkedIn in the chat here in a second too.

00:42:27.479 --> 00:42:29.639
And I'm sorry if sometimes I have to be vague.

00:42:29.639 --> 00:42:34.040
I probably, I don't wanna get myself in hot water

00:42:34.040 --> 00:42:36.760
by sharing results that are probably not shareable.

00:42:37.719 --> 00:42:39.159
That's okay, we're used to that.

00:42:39.560 --> 00:42:43.080
But at least it's not the sports people.

00:42:44.120 --> 00:42:45.959
I'm a sports analytics person.

00:42:45.959 --> 00:42:48.120
We did a thing and it made us win.

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:49.879
Sorry, I can't say anymore.

00:42:51.719 --> 00:42:52.600
Yeah, that's a hard one.

00:42:53.959 --> 00:42:58.040
Scott, I see you had asked a question earlier.

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:01.639
I think it was about Connect, if you wanna jump in.

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:04.600
Yeah, sure.

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:07.479
No, I appreciate this conversation.

00:43:07.479 --> 00:43:10.199
So I'm also in the kind of higher ed data analytics

00:43:10.199 --> 00:43:11.879
and IR world over at Georgetown.

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:15.560
Resonate with a lot of comments about Tableau

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:17.719
and that this space and Power BI

00:43:17.719 --> 00:43:19.719
and everything around it, Looker, you name it.

00:43:20.679 --> 00:43:25.000
But curious, I think I have kind of found a team of folks

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.080
who's really curious and sees an enormous amount

00:43:27.080 --> 00:43:28.760
of potential in the open source space

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:31.800
in the orbit of R and Python and that sort of thing.

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:34.280
And I was curious whether you have a Connect server

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:37.320
up and going, whether you're kind of working with it

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:39.800
in a production fashion or whether you've thought about it

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:42.439
or we're headed in that direction

00:43:42.439 --> 00:43:45.479
and it isn't as common in IR as I might have thought.

00:43:46.760 --> 00:43:49.399
So yeah, just curious about whether you've thought

00:43:49.399 --> 00:43:49.959
in that space.

00:43:51.159 --> 00:43:57.719
We have, and I think that it is certainly a direction

00:43:57.719 --> 00:43:59.080
we'd be interested in pursuing

00:43:59.080 --> 00:44:03.239
is going into open source visualization tools.

00:44:04.199 --> 00:44:06.840
We do have kind of an interoperable,

00:44:06.840 --> 00:44:08.840
multilingual data science team.

00:44:09.639 --> 00:44:11.560
And by the way, this is only on the administrative side.

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:13.320
There are of course probably hundreds

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:14.600
of academic units out there.

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:16.120
Scott, as you know, like who knows

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:18.520
if the physics department has like a massive server

00:44:18.520 --> 00:44:19.479
and they're deploying everything.

00:44:19.479 --> 00:44:20.760
Like who knows, right?

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:21.800
Very possible.

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:23.479
I actually like to give you a sense

00:44:23.479 --> 00:44:25.080
of how decentralized higher ed is.

00:44:25.959 --> 00:44:28.199
It was easier for me to ask Rachel,

00:44:28.199 --> 00:44:32.199
which other people on CU's campus were using Posit

00:44:32.199 --> 00:44:34.040
rather than finding out myself.

00:44:34.040 --> 00:44:35.800
So like that's the world that we're in.

00:44:37.639 --> 00:44:39.320
If anybody wants to know,

00:44:39.320 --> 00:44:42.679
you can always ask me or your own organization.

00:44:42.679 --> 00:44:43.179
Yeah.

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:50.120
So I honestly think that as powerful

00:44:50.120 --> 00:44:51.560
and as great as those tools are,

00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:53.639
we still haven't exactly figured out

00:44:53.639 --> 00:44:54.919
how to make that happen.

00:44:55.719 --> 00:44:58.840
And some of that is kind of tradition

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:01.879
and sort of common use of existing tools.

00:45:02.120 --> 00:45:04.919
And then some of that is the sort of deployment question,

00:45:04.919 --> 00:45:07.239
which is like one of the biggest complaints you get

00:45:07.239 --> 00:45:08.520
when you're working in a bigger organization.

00:45:08.520 --> 00:45:12.040
It's like, please don't give me something else to log into.

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.479
My bookmark bar is already like 900 things.

00:45:17.560 --> 00:45:21.959
But Scott, I would think that

00:45:21.959 --> 00:45:25.560
if you have the appetite to build it,

00:45:25.560 --> 00:45:27.639
and then of course there's like the cost structure around it,

00:45:27.639 --> 00:45:29.560
you know, where, you know,

00:45:29.560 --> 00:45:31.159
deploying something in Posit isn't free,

00:45:31.159 --> 00:45:34.040
but it's definitely cheaper than other options.

00:45:35.239 --> 00:45:36.199
But I would love to connect

00:45:36.199 --> 00:45:38.919
and sort of hear what your journey is like.

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:41.080
We do have a couple of people

00:45:41.080 --> 00:45:42.120
who have built stuff in Shiny,

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:43.080
but then, you know, we go,

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:45.879
well, some end user wants to touch that

00:45:45.879 --> 00:45:46.840
and interact with it.

00:45:46.840 --> 00:45:48.919
And that end user is almost certainly

00:45:48.919 --> 00:45:51.399
not going to have the skills

00:45:51.399 --> 00:45:53.639
to even like fire up an IDE

00:45:53.639 --> 00:45:56.280
and like run the framework.

00:45:57.399 --> 00:46:00.360
So we're probably in early days on that.

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:03.399
But I think what's probably a more likely path

00:46:03.959 --> 00:46:07.399
is that we would at least to start,

00:46:07.399 --> 00:46:09.879
and this is all like just me brainstorming

00:46:09.879 --> 00:46:14.439
in front of 127 people on a high wire,

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:17.879
would be that we would use some of the HTML,

00:46:17.879 --> 00:46:20.040
like the semantic HTML frameworks

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:21.639
that come from open source tools.

00:46:21.639 --> 00:46:24.919
So we would deploy using something like Flex Dashboard

00:46:24.919 --> 00:46:25.639
or something like,

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:27.719
something like, oh my gosh,

00:46:27.719 --> 00:46:29.399
why is my brain falling out of my ear?

00:46:30.919 --> 00:46:35.000
High Chart, which is free use

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:36.520
for academic institutions

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:39.399
to just like deploy HTML web pages

00:46:39.399 --> 00:46:40.760
and put those out there.

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:43.800
I think that would be kind of our like gateway

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:46.520
into a full deployment of something like Shiny.

00:46:49.800 --> 00:46:50.840
Yeah, thanks so much.

00:46:50.840 --> 00:46:52.120
And like, I may ping you later,

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:53.639
because again, we're at the front end

00:46:53.639 --> 00:46:54.840
of this and I think on one hand,

00:46:54.840 --> 00:46:55.800
see a lot of potential,

00:46:55.800 --> 00:46:57.959
but also there's just a lot of inertia elsewhere

00:46:57.959 --> 00:46:59.639
in the organization, as you well know,

00:46:59.639 --> 00:47:01.399
and as we've already talked about this morning.

00:47:01.399 --> 00:47:02.679
So, yep, yep.

00:47:02.679 --> 00:47:04.439
It's a hard problem to move people

00:47:04.439 --> 00:47:06.360
into a new technical space.

00:47:07.239 --> 00:47:08.919
But Scott, I could share some other paths

00:47:08.919 --> 00:47:11.000
we're going down as well, which are pretty cool.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:12.120
Yeah, great, thanks.

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:12.620
Yep.

00:47:15.239 --> 00:47:17.639
I see, Peter, you had a follow-up question.

00:47:17.639 --> 00:47:21.399
I think it was maybe on the weather use case,

00:47:21.399 --> 00:47:22.199
but I'm not sure.

00:47:22.199 --> 00:47:23.399
Do you want to jump in here?

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:27.560
Oh, there you are.

00:47:27.560 --> 00:47:28.199
Oh, sure.

00:47:28.199 --> 00:47:30.840
I was just wondering if your test

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:34.520
to that question was looking at all of the institutions

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:37.959
that they were applying to,

00:47:37.959 --> 00:47:39.959
or if they were only able to look at one.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:41.639
Oh, man.

00:47:41.639 --> 00:47:45.159
If we had comparative data

00:47:45.159 --> 00:47:46.360
across a bunch of institutions,

00:47:46.360 --> 00:47:47.639
that would be amazing,

00:47:47.639 --> 00:47:50.040
but it was just for my single institution.

00:47:50.439 --> 00:47:53.719
And so, yes, I should be a much better data scientist

00:47:53.719 --> 00:47:56.280
and put a bunch of asterisks at the end of that description.

00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:59.159
That finding was limited and localized

00:47:59.159 --> 00:48:01.479
and not generalizable to any institution

00:48:01.479 --> 00:48:03.719
beyond the single one that I did the analysis on

00:48:04.439 --> 00:48:05.959
over the time period that I did it on

00:48:05.959 --> 00:48:07.399
and the population that I did it on.

00:48:08.360 --> 00:48:11.959
So, fully great question.

00:48:13.959 --> 00:48:17.399
You know, Peter, because we have a bunch of

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:19.159
compliance rules,

00:48:19.159 --> 00:48:20.679
you know, there's a federal law called FERPA,

00:48:20.679 --> 00:48:23.320
which is the Federal Education Records Protection Act.

00:48:23.879 --> 00:48:25.639
There's a lot of stuff that we can't share.

00:48:26.199 --> 00:48:31.159
And so, getting a multi-institution level data set

00:48:31.159 --> 00:48:34.360
at the unit of analysis of student level records

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:37.639
is really, really, really complicated.

00:48:39.959 --> 00:48:43.560
And institutions are just very reluctant to share,

00:48:43.560 --> 00:48:45.959
not necessarily, like, we're very,

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:48.360
like, we're very good at sharing.

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:49.879
So, you know, Scott just asked that question

00:48:49.879 --> 00:48:50.919
and I have every confidence.

00:48:50.919 --> 00:48:54.040
Patrick just asked the question that IR people

00:48:54.040 --> 00:48:55.959
or institutional analytics people,

00:48:55.959 --> 00:48:57.080
you all can call me up.

00:48:57.080 --> 00:48:59.000
And one of the best parts about HigherEd

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:00.600
is we all have the same mission.

00:49:00.600 --> 00:49:02.919
We are nominally in competition,

00:49:02.919 --> 00:49:06.840
but we're really trying to just provide an economic ladder,

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:07.800
provide research,

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:10.760
make the world a little bit better of a place.

00:49:10.760 --> 00:49:12.360
So, we're widely collaborative.

00:49:12.360 --> 00:49:13.239
People can call up and go,

00:49:13.239 --> 00:49:13.959
hey, how'd you do this?

00:49:13.959 --> 00:49:15.719
And I will just straight up tell people

00:49:15.719 --> 00:49:16.439
how that worked.

00:49:18.199 --> 00:49:19.639
But the data sharing,

00:49:19.639 --> 00:49:22.600
the ability to do those multi-institutional analyses

00:49:22.600 --> 00:49:25.879
is quite challenging in a lot of cases.

00:49:26.919 --> 00:49:29.320
But one of the things we're actually working on here at CU

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:31.560
is following after the healthcare industry,

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:35.000
we are starting to develop fully synthetic data sets

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:36.439
that will allow us to do that.

00:49:37.479 --> 00:49:39.399
And I don't know many institutions that are doing that,

00:49:39.399 --> 00:49:41.719
but I'm really excited for a future

00:49:41.719 --> 00:49:45.080
where we could create synthetic data sets

00:49:45.080 --> 00:49:47.800
that mirror this essentially the distributions

00:49:47.800 --> 00:49:49.639
that exist in a real data set,

00:49:49.639 --> 00:49:52.760
but don't fall under the data privacy

00:49:52.760 --> 00:49:55.000
and data protections of a federal law.

00:49:56.840 --> 00:49:57.879
But great question, Peter.

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:00.600
I hope I answered that sufficiently.

00:50:03.600 --> 00:50:04.120
Thank you.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.479
AJ, I see you had just asked a question in the chat.

00:50:07.479 --> 00:50:08.520
You wanna jump in here next?

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:12.600
Yeah, sorry if I missed it maybe earlier

00:50:12.600 --> 00:50:13.719
if you mentioned it already,

00:50:13.719 --> 00:50:17.479
but did your company start off with having a data office

00:50:17.479 --> 00:50:19.639
or if not, like what sort of efforts it took

00:50:19.639 --> 00:50:21.719
to create your role?

00:50:21.719 --> 00:50:23.639
Because today a lot of big,

00:50:23.639 --> 00:50:26.040
even big companies sit on piles of data,

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:29.320
but data is something just that's lumped under IT normally.

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:32.360
Just wondering your take on that.

00:50:33.239 --> 00:50:37.879
Yeah, so I haven't been here at CU for too, too long.

00:50:37.879 --> 00:50:40.280
So the history is maybe a little bit murky,

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:44.040
but pretty much every university has had an office

00:50:44.679 --> 00:50:46.840
that's typically called institutional research

00:50:47.879 --> 00:50:51.159
that has focused on these kinds of analytic questions.

00:50:51.159 --> 00:50:52.280
And then of course,

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:55.399
reporting to the various agencies that require reporting.

00:50:55.399 --> 00:50:56.280
So here in Colorado,

00:50:56.280 --> 00:50:57.719
we have a bunch of requirements

00:50:57.719 --> 00:50:59.639
that we report to the state of Colorado.

00:50:59.639 --> 00:51:02.679
We have a bunch of connections with the city of Boulder

00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:05.320
to make sure that we're integrated there.

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:08.520
We have a bunch of connections with the federal government

00:51:08.520 --> 00:51:10.040
because of Title IV funding,

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:11.719
because of research funding.

00:51:11.719 --> 00:51:14.600
So we have a lot of data needs

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:17.560
to make sure that we are being in compliance

00:51:17.560 --> 00:51:19.479
and that we're being as effective as possible.

00:51:20.040 --> 00:51:23.639
So the kind of tradition of having a data office

00:51:23.639 --> 00:51:25.719
in higher ed goes way back.

00:51:25.719 --> 00:51:28.439
I mean, decades and decades and decades.

00:51:28.439 --> 00:51:31.479
But as the sort of appetite for data has grown

00:51:31.479 --> 00:51:34.919
and as the appetite for people to make smarter decisions

00:51:34.919 --> 00:51:37.959
and more sort of data informed decisions has grown,

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:40.439
these data conversations

00:51:40.439 --> 00:51:41.879
have gotten bigger and bigger and bigger.

00:51:41.879 --> 00:51:43.159
So do you have someone who's there

00:51:43.159 --> 00:51:45.159
to deploy and analyze surveys?

00:51:45.159 --> 00:51:46.760
Do you have somebody who is there

00:51:47.719 --> 00:51:50.840
to do research on how faculty are performing,

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:53.159
to have, to understand how students are performing,

00:51:53.159 --> 00:51:56.919
to really think through not just how many questions,

00:51:56.919 --> 00:51:59.879
but what is the relationship between X and Y questions?

00:52:00.840 --> 00:52:03.719
And then finally, the third kind of layer of that

00:52:03.719 --> 00:52:07.000
is just like, how do we make the best use of our data

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.159
in a secure and a systematic way?

00:52:09.159 --> 00:52:10.199
How do we democratize it?

00:52:10.199 --> 00:52:10.919
How do we scale it?

00:52:10.919 --> 00:52:11.800
How do we govern it?

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:15.719
And so I would say that like every university,

00:52:15.719 --> 00:52:16.840
no matter how big or small,

00:52:16.840 --> 00:52:19.639
I mean, the smallest community college anywhere

00:52:20.760 --> 00:52:26.040
probably has some, even if it's one person,

00:52:26.040 --> 00:52:27.879
some person who's doing analytic work.

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:32.120
But I think having kind of a centralized,

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:36.040
systematic networked office

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:39.239
that's responsible for thinking about data as an asset

00:52:39.239 --> 00:52:41.239
is probably a growing trend.

00:52:43.239 --> 00:52:45.879
But I went to like a Gartner thing a year or two ago

00:52:45.879 --> 00:52:47.399
and they had like a little higher ed table

00:52:47.399 --> 00:52:48.840
and it was like, oh, so you're the six,

00:52:49.399 --> 00:52:50.919
but I imagine that you go a year from now

00:52:50.919 --> 00:52:51.639
and there'll be 12.

00:52:51.639 --> 00:52:52.840
And I imagine you go a year from then,

00:52:52.840 --> 00:52:57.320
there'll be 40 and higher ed is often last to the party,

00:52:58.439 --> 00:53:01.719
but we kind of track the trends that go on

00:53:01.959 --> 00:53:03.560
in industry quite often.

00:53:03.560 --> 00:53:06.280
Thank you.

00:53:07.399 --> 00:53:08.040
Oh, sorry.

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:10.600
Oh, no, I was just saying, thank you.

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:11.399
Thank you.

00:53:11.399 --> 00:53:11.899
Of course.

00:53:12.679 --> 00:53:15.479
Thank you all for the great questions too.

00:53:15.479 --> 00:53:18.760
As we get to the top of the hour here,

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:19.959
if there's anything I missed,

00:53:19.959 --> 00:53:22.199
feel free to raise your hand here on Zoom

00:53:22.199 --> 00:53:25.159
so I can see it as well and can call you in here.

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:28.280
But Brad, one question, actually,

00:53:28.280 --> 00:53:30.919
one of my colleagues had asked this earlier,

00:53:30.919 --> 00:53:32.840
but they mentioned they saw something online

00:53:32.840 --> 00:53:35.959
that you host a community of practice event

00:53:36.600 --> 00:53:39.959
and was just curious to learn like how that came together

00:53:39.959 --> 00:53:41.399
and how you publicized it.

00:53:43.479 --> 00:53:44.919
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:53:44.919 --> 00:53:49.239
So there was an online community of practice,

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:52.840
there was sort of a Zoom meeting when I first joined CU

00:53:53.639 --> 00:53:55.800
and what we find,

00:53:55.800 --> 00:53:57.159
and I think this gets back a little bit

00:53:57.159 --> 00:53:58.199
to Deepa's question,

00:53:58.199 --> 00:53:58.760
which is like,

00:53:59.320 --> 00:54:03.080
how do you get people to sort of be in the experience?

00:54:03.719 --> 00:54:06.280
And the College of Engineering has analysts

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:08.919
and all these places have analysts

00:54:08.919 --> 00:54:12.040
and they all have people who are working on similar problems.

00:54:12.040 --> 00:54:17.800
And so the better we are able to coordinate everybody

00:54:17.800 --> 00:54:20.360
and the better we're able to sort of work with everybody,

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:21.000
the better we do.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.000
So we built out this data community of practice

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.080
and it was a Zoom thing and we invited some guests

00:54:25.080 --> 00:54:27.639
and I haven't looked through the whole list here,

00:54:27.639 --> 00:54:31.000
but I may have hit some of you up to be guests at some point.

00:54:31.560 --> 00:54:33.399
I know one person in particular,

00:54:34.439 --> 00:54:36.199
but anyway, we'd have people come in

00:54:36.199 --> 00:54:38.600
and talk about data governance or master data management

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:40.679
or we'd have people come in and talk about different things.

00:54:40.679 --> 00:54:43.560
And the idea sort of surfaced of like,

00:54:44.199 --> 00:54:45.719
we're all kind of tired of staring at each other

00:54:45.719 --> 00:54:46.840
on Zoom a little bit.

00:54:46.840 --> 00:54:48.919
This is amazing because you're all distributed

00:54:48.919 --> 00:54:49.639
all over the world,

00:54:49.639 --> 00:54:54.040
but we have a need to build this community.

00:54:54.040 --> 00:54:55.879
And so we decided to have an event

00:54:55.879 --> 00:54:57.239
and we actually jokingly,

00:54:57.239 --> 00:54:59.879
I mean, I name things so stupidly.

00:54:59.879 --> 00:55:01.879
The biggest problem in computer science is naming things.

00:55:01.879 --> 00:55:03.800
It's why I'm never going to be a computer scientist

00:55:03.800 --> 00:55:05.959
because I'm terrible at naming things.

00:55:05.959 --> 00:55:08.360
But we straight up went with like IRL,

00:55:08.360 --> 00:55:10.919
like we're going to have a data community practice conference

00:55:10.919 --> 00:55:12.040
in real life.

00:55:12.040 --> 00:55:13.800
And let's all get into the room together

00:55:13.800 --> 00:55:15.239
and let's focus on a couple of things.

00:55:15.879 --> 00:55:18.439
One, we wanted to do some actual technical training

00:55:18.439 --> 00:55:20.360
and provide that value to our campus.

00:55:20.360 --> 00:55:22.600
So we had one training session that was in R

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:23.959
in the tidyverse

00:55:23.959 --> 00:55:25.639
and we had another one that was in Tableau.

00:55:26.600 --> 00:55:28.760
And it was just a chance to sort of take

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:30.679
some real experts in that

00:55:30.679 --> 00:55:32.919
and lift a bunch of boats all at once.

00:55:34.360 --> 00:55:36.520
And then we had some sort of broader conversations,

00:55:36.520 --> 00:55:38.360
including a keynote speaker who spoke

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.399
about the need to think about data

00:55:41.399 --> 00:55:42.679
in more equitable ways.

00:55:43.479 --> 00:55:45.399
We are constantly having this conversation

00:55:45.399 --> 00:55:48.760
about these important conversations

00:55:48.760 --> 00:55:50.280
around diversity and equity

00:55:50.280 --> 00:55:52.040
and around racism and anti-racism.

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:55.399
And believe it or not,

00:55:55.399 --> 00:55:57.239
if you haven't spent time thinking about it,

00:55:57.239 --> 00:55:58.600
the way you collect data,

00:55:58.600 --> 00:55:59.879
the way you capture data,

00:55:59.879 --> 00:56:02.360
the way you count people matters.

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:05.800
And so we brought in someone who is an expert in this.

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:07.159
His name is Carson Bird.

00:56:07.159 --> 00:56:08.679
We brought him in from the University of Michigan

00:56:08.679 --> 00:56:10.280
to really talk to everybody

00:56:10.280 --> 00:56:12.840
and to have like a thought provoking conversation

00:56:12.840 --> 00:56:16.679
around the ways that data may or may not reflect

00:56:16.679 --> 00:56:18.760
the communities that we're trying to represent.

00:56:20.600 --> 00:56:22.199
And then we also gave people the opportunity

00:56:22.199 --> 00:56:23.159
to do some lightning talks,

00:56:23.159 --> 00:56:25.159
which were absolutely amazing.

00:56:25.719 --> 00:56:28.360
We invited people from around campus to basically say,

00:56:28.360 --> 00:56:30.199
for 15 minutes, you have the opportunity

00:56:30.199 --> 00:56:32.439
to talk about a problem that is vexing you.

00:56:33.159 --> 00:56:38.439
And I cannot tell you enough how cool it was.

00:56:39.080 --> 00:56:41.639
And I would recommend it to any of your organizations

00:56:41.639 --> 00:56:43.959
to not only stand up a community of practice

00:56:43.959 --> 00:56:45.959
and just to get people together and say like,

00:56:45.959 --> 00:56:46.919
hey, what are you working on?

00:56:46.919 --> 00:56:48.439
What problems do you have?

00:56:48.439 --> 00:56:49.800
But to occasionally do your best

00:56:49.800 --> 00:56:51.159
to try and get everybody together

00:56:52.040 --> 00:56:54.760
in a meaningful way.

00:56:54.760 --> 00:56:57.159
Because people walked out of that, in my view,

00:56:57.959 --> 00:56:59.800
not only technically better,

00:56:59.800 --> 00:57:02.600
but with the ability to sit down and eat lunch

00:57:02.600 --> 00:57:04.679
with that person who sits across campus

00:57:04.679 --> 00:57:06.280
and is working on the same thing.

00:57:07.080 --> 00:57:10.600
So the Zoom thing came together before me,

00:57:10.600 --> 00:57:12.040
but we kind of were like, you know what?

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:14.439
Let's get off Zoom for a day and a half.

00:57:14.439 --> 00:57:17.399
And it was a ton of fun.

00:57:17.399 --> 00:57:18.120
Highly recommend.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:20.199
I love that.

00:57:20.199 --> 00:57:21.879
Love anything to do with community.

00:57:21.879 --> 00:57:23.159
That sounds awesome.

00:57:23.159 --> 00:57:25.080
Okay, we have a few minutes here,

00:57:25.080 --> 00:57:28.520
so I might just rapid fire the remaining questions to you.

00:57:28.520 --> 00:57:31.080
All right, I'll see if I can do them in like 20 seconds.

00:57:31.080 --> 00:57:32.199
Let's see how many we can get through.

00:57:32.199 --> 00:57:36.040
Tsering asked, have you done any analysis

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:38.199
of the chances of a student

00:57:38.199 --> 00:57:41.479
successfully finishing a course or failing out?

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:45.959
Yeah, that's a really, really common type of analysis

00:57:45.959 --> 00:57:47.080
that happens in higher ed

00:57:47.080 --> 00:57:49.159
is trying to estimate a student's likelihood.

00:57:50.120 --> 00:57:55.080
But again, we're not here to filter people out

00:57:55.080 --> 00:57:56.360
or to make people feel...

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.000
There isn't some sort of channel for that.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:02.199
What it allows us to do

00:58:02.199 --> 00:58:04.120
is it allows us to focus our resources,

00:58:04.120 --> 00:58:05.320
like any predictive model,

00:58:05.879 --> 00:58:09.320
on the students that might need additional help.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.199
So if we can estimate that a student

00:58:12.199 --> 00:58:14.760
might not be successful in a particular class,

00:58:14.760 --> 00:58:16.520
it isn't like, don't take that class.

00:58:16.520 --> 00:58:18.280
It's what support can we give you

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:19.479
so that you are successful?

00:58:21.080 --> 00:58:21.560
Thank you.

00:58:21.560 --> 00:58:23.639
And I think you answered this one in the chat,

00:58:23.639 --> 00:58:25.959
but is there a likelihood of colleges

00:58:25.959 --> 00:58:29.239
to move to AWS or Azure completely?

00:58:29.959 --> 00:58:33.239
Yeah, I mean, hang out in my email for a day

00:58:33.239 --> 00:58:34.600
and you'll see that higher ed,

00:58:34.600 --> 00:58:36.120
I mean, it's a massive industry.

00:58:36.120 --> 00:58:37.560
There are thousands of universities.

00:58:38.600 --> 00:58:40.760
And yes, there are institutions

00:58:40.760 --> 00:58:44.760
that have fully gone into a variety of cloud environments

00:58:44.760 --> 00:58:45.879
for a variety of reasons.

00:58:46.840 --> 00:58:49.320
So no doubt.

00:58:51.800 --> 00:58:52.280
Cool.

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:55.639
And I think maybe one last question I missed

00:58:55.639 --> 00:58:58.120
was you talked about synthetic data sets.

00:58:58.120 --> 00:59:00.840
Do you have any packages you could recommend or approaches?

00:59:02.439 --> 00:59:03.959
I would need to get back to you.

00:59:03.959 --> 00:59:07.000
I think that we're building those in Python

00:59:07.879 --> 00:59:10.760
and my Pythonic chops are a little bit weaker.

00:59:10.760 --> 00:59:12.520
So I could find out what we're using.

00:59:12.840 --> 00:59:18.040
And yes, I forgot to drop my favorite fun fact,

00:59:18.040 --> 00:59:21.080
which is that IPython was a side project

00:59:21.080 --> 00:59:25.320
of a grad student at CU Boulder in the early 2000s.

00:59:25.320 --> 00:59:29.000
So Fernando Perez is a physicist

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:32.040
and realized it wasn't an interactive way to touch Python.

00:59:32.040 --> 00:59:34.439
And so there's some lab around here

00:59:34.439 --> 00:59:39.080
in which IPython and subsequently Jupyter were born.

00:59:39.080 --> 00:59:43.719
So depending on your view of CU, of Jupyter notebooks,

00:59:44.760 --> 00:59:46.439
either you're welcome or I'm sorry.

00:59:49.639 --> 00:59:51.560
